  "method": "We propose Privileged-to-Visual Meta-Distillation with Flow-Stabilized Perception (PVM-Flow), a sim-to-real pipeline that minimizes real-world supervision while addressing both visual and dynamics gaps. First, build a calibrated digital twin of the task and learn a high-performance privileged (state-based) policy entirely in simulation. Train it across a wide range of randomized dynamics and visual factors so the resulting behavior is robust and diverse; concurrently, meta-train the policy for fast adaptation by optimizing expected return after a few inner-loop updates. This privileged expert is then used to generate a large set of successful trajectories in sim.\n\nSecond, distill the expert into a visuomotor policy by behavior cloning from RGB(+proprio) to actions using the simulated trajectories. During cloning, aggressively randomize cameras, lighting, textures, and distractors, and apply strong visual augmentations. To suppress spurious background cues at train and test time, segment and mask static backgrounds and track the manipulated objects across time. In the visuomotor encoder, stabilize perception by aggregating features over a short window of recent frames: estimate optical flow to warp neighboring-frame features into the current frame and fuse them with spatially varying, similarity-based weights. This flow-guided temporal fusion reduces sensitivity to motion blur and sensor noise without needing extra labels.\n\nThird, incorporate a very small number of real-world rollouts (e.g., 5–20) from the policy to anchor the distribution shift. Mix these real samples with simulated demonstrations at equal sampling probability when training or fine-tuning the visuomotor policy and any value function, which regularizes estimates on real transitions and prevents overreliance on simulated statistics. Keep the visual encoder largely frozen and adapt lightweight adapters or the control head to avoid overfitting. Optionally, use unlabeled real images to run brief self-supervised consistency or augmentation-invariance updates on the encoder to align low-level statistics without requiring annotations.\n\nFinally, perform fast on-robot adaptation at deployment with a few safe inner-loop updates: collect K short episodes, compute on-policy gradients, and update only the control head and dynamics-sensitive layers while freezing most perception. Repeat this receding-horizon meta-update sparingly (e.g., every few episodes) with conservative step sizes and safety constraints. Add newly successful real trajectories to the demo buffer (dataset aggregation) to further improve performance over time, while continuing to leverage the large simulated corpus.",
  "rationale": "This design separates what simulation does best (training a strong privileged expert over broad dynamics and visuals) from what must be learned from pixels and from hardware (robust perception and quick dynamics adaptation). Privileged-to-visual distillation transfers task knowledge to a vision policy with extensive visual randomization and background masking, shrinking the appearance gap. Mixing a handful of real rollouts at equal sampling combats critic or policy miscalibration on real transitions without requiring many demonstrations.\n\nA MAML-style inner-loop at deployment explicitly targets the remaining dynamics mismatch using only a few safe on-hardware rollouts, while freezing most of perception to preserve visual robustness. Flow-guided temporal feature aggregation makes the visuomotor encoder resilient to real-world sensing artifacts (blur, rolling shutter, flicker) without extra labels, further reducing the need for real demonstrations. Together, these ingredients address both the physics/dynamics and vision gaps with minimal real data.",
