  "method": "Phase 0 — Sim pretraining + real-calibrated sensor rendering (digital twin). Train a visuomotor policy in simulation with broad domain randomization, but render observations through a lightweight digital-twin sensor model fitted from a few minutes of unlabeled real logs. For cameras, estimate intrinsics, rolling-shutter timing, vignetting, color/ISP and noise–blur statistics and plug them into the renderer; for any available tactile/force sensors, calibrate simple transfer functions and noise. This pretraining yields a teacher policy and features already biased toward the real sensor physics without requiring labeled real demonstrations.\n\nPhase 1 — Visual alignment on real via uncertainty-guided visual prompts. Freeze the policy backbone and learn pixel-level visual prompts added to real images so their intermediate features align to the sim-trained distribution. Train prompts with two weak-supervision signals: (a) adversarial feature alignment using a domain discriminator with a gradient reversal layer to make real features indistinguishable from simulated ones; and (b) pseudo-label knowledge transfer from the sim-trained teacher on real frames. Weight each update by a per-sample uncertainty score: confident samples update prompts strongly while uncertain ones are downweighted via an EMA-style scheduler. A small seed of human-labeled demonstrations anchors the objective but most images can be unlabeled.\n\nPhase 2 — Dynamics adaptor with shared vs domain-specific latents. Factor the policy’s action latent into a shared component z_shared and a domain-specific component z_dom. Keep the encoder and decoder largely fixed; learn a compact domain-specific prior over z_dom and a tiny residual in the action decoder using a short set of real rollouts. Regularize with KL to the sim prior on z_shared and keep z_shared frozen so that only dynamics- and actuation-specific variability is absorbed by z_dom. This concentrates real-data sample complexity on the few parameters that model friction, latency, and contact nuances.\n\nPhase 3 — On-policy data aggregation with a pseudo demonstrator. Run the adapted policy on hardware and aggregate data DAgger-style. At each visited state, invoke a pseudo-interactive demonstrator (planner or MPC with privileged maps/geometry when available) to produce target actions. Mix these pseudo-targets with the limited human demonstrations to fine-tune the policy. Gate supervision with uncertainty: accept pseudo-labels only when the policy is confident; otherwise, request a human correction or fall back to a safe controller. This keeps real human interventions minimal while covering the on-policy state distribution.\n\nPhase 4 — Causal multiscale sensor fusion wrapper for deployment. Wrap the high-level visuomotor policy with a discretely-online Neural CDE that fuses low-rate visual embeddings with high-rate proprioception/IMU/force at the control frequency, ensuring strict causality. Fine-tune only the CDE drift/readout on a few minutes of real trajectories (behavior cloning or self-supervised consistency), leaving the visuomotor backbone intact. This multirate, causal fusion compensates residual sensor and dynamics mismatch at run time without substantial additional demonstrations.",
  "rationale": "The sim-to-real gap splits cleanly into perception and dynamics. A real-calibrated digital-twin renderer narrows the gap before training even starts, and uncertainty-guided visual prompts further pull real images into the sim-trained feature geometry with little or no labeling. On the dynamics side, a shared/domain-specific latent decomposition localizes real-data adaptation to a tiny prior and residual head that capture friction, delay, and contact differences, while a causal Neural CDE layer fuses fast proprioception with vision to stabilize control under real sensor timing and noise.\n\nMinimal demonstrations are achieved by combining weakly supervised adaptation (adversarial alignment and pseudo-label KD), active uncertainty gating to decide when to trust pseudo-labels or request help, and DAgger-style on-policy relabeling with a pseudo demonstrator so that most corrections do not require a human. Constraining real-world learning to small modules (prompts, z_dom prior, and the CDE wrapper) concentrates capacity where the gap lives and keeps the data footprint and risk low.",
